 TypeScript is a statically-typed superset of JavaScript that adds optional types, classes, and modules to the language. It's designed to help catch errors early during development and improve code maintainability by providing better tooling and autocompletion. TypeScript compiles down to plain JavaScript, making it a great choice for large-scale JavaScript projects.

Duck typing is a programming concept that allows objects with compatible interfaces to be treated as equivalent, even if their implementations are different. The name comes from the phrase "if it looks like a duck, swims like a duck, and quacks like a duck, then it probably is a duck." In TypeScript, this concept is implemented through structural typing, which focuses on the shape of the object rather than its implementation.

For example, consider two objects:

```typescript
interface Duck {
  walk: () => void;
  quack: () => void;
}

const duck1: Duck = {
  walk: () => console.log("Duck 1 is walking"),
  quack: () => console.log("Duck 1 is quacking"),
};

const duck2: any = {
  walk: () => console.log("Duck 2 is walking"),
  quack: () => console.log("Duck 2 is quacking"),
  fly: () => console.log("Duck 2 is flying"),
};

duck1.walk();
duck1.quack();

duck2.walk();
duck2.quack();

// TypeScript will not complain about the following call, even though Duck2 has an extra method
duck1.fly(); // Output: Duck 1 is flying
```

In this example, even though `duck2` has an extra method `fly()`, TypeScript allows the call to `duck1.fly()` because both objects have the same structure (i.e., the same keys and types for the `walk` and `quack` methods). This is an example of duck typing in TypeScript.

 To create a Discord bot using Discord.js v14 with a slash command named `ban`, follow the steps below:

1. First, make sure you have Node.js installed on your system. If not, download and install it from https://nodejs.org/en/download/.

2. Create a new directory for your bot project and initialize it with npm:

```bash
mkdir discord-ban-bot
cd discord-ban-bot
npm init -y
```

3. Install Discord.js and other required packages:

```bash
npm install discord.js @discordjs/slash
```

4. Create a new file named `index.js` and add the following code:

```javascript
const { Client, Intents, SlashCommandBuilder } = require('discord.js');
const { SlashCommandBuilder } = require('@discordjs/slash');

const client = new Client({ intents: [Intents.FLAGS.Guilds, Intents.FLAGS.GuildMessages, Intents.FLAGS.GuildMembers] });

const banCommand = new SlashCommandBuilder()
  .setName('ban')
  .setDescription('Bans a user from the server')
  .addUserOption((option) =>
    option.setName('user').setDescription('The user to ban').setRequired(true))
  .addStringOption((option) =>
    option.setName('reason').setDescription('The reason for the ban').setRequired(false));

client.commands = new Map();
client.commands.set('ban', banCommand);

client.on('interactionCreate', async (interaction) => {
  if (!interaction.isCommand()) return;

  const command = client.commands.get(interaction.commandName);

  if (!command) return;

  try {
    await interaction.reply({ content: 'Processing...', fetchReply: true });

    const user = interaction.options.getUser('user');
    const reason = interaction.options.getString('reason');

    await interaction.guild.members.ban(user, { reason });

    await interaction.editReply({ content: `User ${user.tag} has been banned. Reason: ${reason || 'No reason provided.'}` });
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(error);
    await interaction.editReply({ content: 'There was an error trying to process that command!', ephemeral: true });
  }
});

client.login('YOUR_BOT_TOKEN');
```

Replace `YOUR_BOT_TOKEN` with your bot's token.

5. Start the bot:

```bash
node index.js
```

Now, your bot is online and ready to use the `ban` command. Users can use it by typing `/ban @user [reason]` in any server where the bot has been invited.

 Here's a simple C++ function that uses the `cmark` library to convert markdown formatted text to HTML. Before using this function, make sure you have the `libcmark` library installed. You can find the installation instructions on the project's GitHub page: https://github.com/commonmark/cmark

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <cmark.h>

std::string markdown_to_html(const std::string& markdown) {
    cmark_parser parser;
    cmark_language language = cmark_language_load("en-US");
    cmark_document document = cmark_parse(&parser, language, markdown.c_str(), markdown.size(), 0);
    const char* html = cmark_render_html(document);

    std::string result(html);
    cmark_free(document);
    cmark_parser_free(parser);
    cmark_language_free(language);

    return result;
}
```

This function takes a `std::string` containing markdown formatted text as an argument and returns a `std::string` containing the corresponding HTML formatted text. The `cmark` library is used to parse the markdown and generate the HTML. Make sure to link the `libcmark` library when compiling your code.

