 Here's a simple C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
#include <vector>
#include <sstream>

int main() {
    std::string fileName, wordToFind, line;
    int count = 0;

    std::cout << "Enter the file name: ";
    std::cin >> fileName;
    std::cout << "Enter the word to find: ";
    std::cin >> wordToFind;

    std::ifstream file(fileName);

    if (file.is_open()) {
        while (std::getline(file, line)) {
            std::istringstream iss(line);
            std::string word;
            while (iss >> word) {
                if (word == wordToFind) {
                    count++;
                }
            }
        }
        file.close();
    } else {
        std::cout << "Unable to open file";
        return 1; // return with error code 1
    }

    std::cout << "The word '" << wordToFind << "' occurs " << count << " times in the file.";

    return 0;
}
```

This program takes the file name and the word to find as input from the user. It opens the file and reads it line by line. For each line, it uses a string stream to split the line into words and checks if each word matches the word to find. If a match is found, the count is incremented. After reading all lines, the program closes the file and displays the number of occurrences of the word in the file.
